Getting the two albums in one dataframe

artist_albums <- tribble(
  ~artist, ~album,
  "CÃ©line Dion", "All the Way... A Decade of Song",
  "Madonna", "Ray of Light"
)

df <- artist_albums %>%
  add_genius(artist, album)

# unnesting so that each word is a row
unnested_df <- df %>%
  unnest_tokens(word, lyric)

# removing stop words
df2 <- unnested_df %>% 
  anti_join(custom_stop_words)

Below I will create a graph that will explicitly show which artist is more positive by the ânrcâ lexicon:

sentiment_count <- df2 %>% 
  inner_join(get_sentiments("nrc"), by = "word") %>% 
  count(sentiment, artist) %>% 
  spread(sentiment, n, fill = 0)


sentiment_count %>%
  mutate(score = (positive - negative) / (positive + negative)) %>%
  mutate(artist = reorder(artist, score)) %>%
  ggplot(aes(artist, score, fill = score > 0)) +
  geom_col(show.legend = FALSE, fill = "pink") +
  coord_flip() +
  labs(x = "Artist",
       y = "Positivity score among artists") +
  ggtitle("Who is more positive?")

Here we can clearly see that CÃ©line Dionâs positivity score is much higher.

Tf-idf

I will now use the stringr library to produce my tf_idf charts. Tf-idf helps to define what are the most important words used by the artists.

library(stringr)

# create td idf dataframe

df2_tf_idf <- df2 %>%
  count(artist, word) %>%
  filter(!str_detect(word, "\\d+")) %>%
  bind_tf_idf(word, artist, n) %>%
  arrange(-tf_idf)

# create tf-idf chart

df2_tf_idf %>%    
  arrange(desc(tf_idf)) %>%
  mutate(word = factor(word, levels = rev(unique(word)))) %>% 
  group_by(artist) %>% 
  top_n(10) %>% 
  ungroup %>%
  ggplot(aes(word, tf_idf, fill = artist)) +
  geom_col(show.legend = FALSE) +
  labs(x = NULL, y = "tf-idf") +
  facet_wrap(~artist, ncol = 2, scales = "free") +
  coord_flip() +
  ggtitle("What's important?")

Tf-idf will show how important one words is for the artists. Again we can see that the topics that arise as âimportantâ for CÃ©line Dion are more in the romantic- dreamy field, whereas for Madonna it is much more down to Earth, and less about emotions.

LDA- Topic Modelling

Letâs see what different topics lie within the lines of these songs, using Latent Dirichlet Allocation. I will be creating 2 topics, and see what type of words I get in each.

topics <- LDA(cast_dtm(data = df2 %>% 
               count(artist, word) %>% 
               ungroup(),
             term = word,
             document = artist, 
             value = n),
    k = 2, control = list(seed = 42)) %>% 
  tidy(matrix = "beta") %>% 
  group_by(topic) %>%
  arrange(desc(beta)) %>% 
  top_n(12, beta) %>% 
  ungroup()
topics %>% 
  arrange(topic, -beta) %>% 
  mutate(term = reorder(term, beta)) %>% 
  ggplot(aes(term, beta, fill = factor(topic))) +
  geom_col(show.legend = FALSE) +
  facet_wrap(~ topic, scales = 'free') +
  coord_flip() +
  ggtitle(" Topic modeling using LDA")

Using topic modelling, we are able to make the distinction between Madonnaâs and CÃ©line Dionâs âwordsâ. It is clearly visible that Madonnaâs words were collected into one of the topics, a topic that to me seems much more down to Earth, versus CÃ©line Dionâs collection of words which are much more about feelings, than activity.

Conclusion

My hypothesis, that CÃ©line Dionâs song are more positive than Madonnaâs seem to be proved right.This is one of the rare cases when the hypothesis cannot be rejected.

I first looked at the overall frequency of the words available in the two albums. Since the word âloveâ is one of the most positive words, I first checked which artist uses it more. The word love was used by CÃ©line Dion much more frequently than by Madonna.

Then I looked at the sentiments present in the dataset, also for the individual artists. I also checked which were the most common positive and negative sentiment words, as well as which words contributed most to the various sentiments ( positive or negative). It seemed that Madonna had more words that were contributing to negative sentiments, than CÃ©line Dion.

I used the nrc lexicon to check and visualize who is more positive overall. The answer was clear: CÃ©line Dion.

I also looked at wordclouds to get an overall picture of what words were used most frequenty by the two artists. Comparison cloud helped to visualize the weight of positive and negative words, in the wordcloud.

Using the tf-idf method I was able to identify what words seem to be the most important for the two artists. I was able to derive that for CÃ©line Dion most words defined by the tf-idf method were about emotions, whereas for Madonna they were more down to Earth and active.

To check on my previous findings, I used LDA Topic Modelling to see what the LDA is going to find. I purposely indicated 2 categories, and checked how it divides the words.The pattern that we have seen previously was also visible here, one category was much more active, while the other much more emotional.
